ically distinguished between categories of migrants-such as labor, refugee, family, and postcolonial migrants. Covering France, the United States, Turkey, Canada, Mexico, the Netherlands, Sweden, and Denmark, the contributors explain how concepts such as "refugee," "family," and "difference" have been defined through policy and public debate. Tightly intertwined, these definitions are continuously changing with the economic and geopolitical climate, as well as in relation to migrants' gender, class, ethnicity, religion, sexual orientation, and countries of destination and origin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aEmigration and immigrationxGovernment policyzWestern countries. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSex differences. 0aEmigration and immigrationxSocial aspectszWestern countries. 0aImmigrant familiesxGovernment policyzWestern countries. 0aWomen immigrantszWestern countries. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAndreassen, Rikke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyd, Monica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCederberg, Maja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Guno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLegêne, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoloney, Deirdre M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMoloney, Deirdre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNowak, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOxford, Connie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaissiguier, Catheri